post_text:
Happy Wildcat Wednesday!

Wildcat LAIR seeks to promote leadership, achievement, integrity, and responsibility, and it's always encouraging when members of the community call to tell us about students who exemplify these traits.

A-J Wildcat Zachary Stokes saw a neighbor in need and opted to help. Since that time, Stokes has gone above and beyond, completing small tasks some people may not give a second thought; however, to the recipient of his acts of kindness? We're told his actions meant the world.

This Wildcat Wednesday we're glad to take the opportunity to recognize Zach Stokes with a gift card to Sonic because he's clearly a reason we're #AJProud

To further honor him and his random act of kindness, we'd like to hear from you. In the comments, please nominate someone to win a $10 Hebrewz gift card.

Nominees should be from the Anna-Jonesboro area and nominated for their random acts of kindness. Nominations close at midnight tonight. Give us another reason to celebrate, #WildcatNation !

post_text:
The Seniors of Anna-Jonesboro Community High School will undoubtedly be missed, and we are proud of who they've grown to be over the last four years. We cannot replace the parts of their senior year taken by this unprecedented situation; however, we can attempt to embrace the uncertainty in the best way possible. The late comedienne Gilda Radner said it best: "I wanted a perfect ending. Now I've learned, the hard way, that some poems don't rhyme, and some stories don't have a clear beginning, middle, and end. Life is about not knowing, having to change, taking the moment and making the best of it, without knowing what's going to happen next."

We want to celebrate each of our A-J Seniors.

Josi Jerrell is the daughter of Shawn and Crystal Jerrell. After graduation, Josi plans to attend Shawnee Community College and pursue a degree in nursing.

Congratulations, Josi! You’re one more reason to be #ajproud !

AJCHS Class of 2020:
Today “should’ve been” the day family, friends and the community gather to honor the Class of 2020 at the school. While we still plan to have a graduation ceremony in June, we know many students and their families have a bit of bittersweet sadness today.

While this video changes nothing in our world, know that the Board or Education, administration, faculty and staff at AJ love you and want nothing but wonderful things for you! The few words of advice contained in this video do not encompass all the advice we’ve hopefully given you over the last four years, but we hope it reminds you of all the lessons you’ve learned while at AJ.

We love and miss each of you, and cannot wait to celebrate with your class in-person as soon as we are able!

#ajproud

post_text: Congratulations to the 2 recipients of the Spanish Club Scholarship this year! Braden Benns and Soren Poulos Keller will each receive a scholarship in the amount of $250 from the Spanish Club. The Spanish Club Scholarship goes to two students who have been active members of Spanish Club for all 4 years, who have taken Spanish classes all 4 years of their high school careers, and who have the highest GPA in their Spanish courses. This year, Braden Benns and Soren Poulos Keller were both officers of Spanish Club, as well. ¡Felicidades, Braden y Soren!

post_text: In its most recent guidance, the Illinois State Board of Education indicated that with Governor Pritzker's extension of the stay-at-home order through May 30, in-person graduation ceremonies are not allowed through the end of the academic year. Therefore, the original graduation date of May 16th has been officially postponed until the alternate date of June 27th, when it is hoped that group gatherings will be deemed safe and allowable. We will continue to monitor guidance from ISBE, and we will continue to communicate any developments.
text: In its most recent guidance, the Illinois State Board of Education indicated that with Governor Pritzker's extension of the stay-at-home order through May 30, in-person graduation ceremonies are not allowed through the end of the academic year. Therefore, the original graduation date of May 16th has been officially postponed until the alternate date of June 27th, when it is hoped that group gatherings will be deemed safe and allowable. We will continue to monitor guidance from ISBE, and we will continue to communicate any developments.

post_text:
Per Governor Pritzker’s most recent press conference, we regret to inform you we will not be meeting in the classroom again for the duration of the 2019-2020 school year. Instead, we will continue educating students via remote learning.

Students, your faculty and staff are incredibly sad this school year is ending in this unanticipated way; however, we remain available and willing to help, encourage, and guide you in any way possible. Graduation plans are being discussed by administration and the Board and every effort will be made to honor our wonderful graduates.

We’ll continue to share any updates or guidance as we receive it from the ISBE. #ajproud

The ACES team, formally known as WYSE, competed in Sectional competition at SIU on March 11th. Due to errors in the scoring system, the teams just received their score late in the evening on March 21st. For the first time in many years (we have confirmation we went to state in 1998; can anyone determine if we’ve been since?) the A-J ACES will advance to state competition. The team received third place overall, with the following students placing in their individual subjects:

Lily Yana: 1st Math
Abby Sartin: 3rd Math
Peyton Otey: 1st English and 2nd Physics
Morgan Keller: 3rd English
Connor Hallam: 2nd Physics

Another HUGE reason to be #ajproud

post_text:
In the midst of the COVID-19 closures, teachers at A-J are still working to support their students. Meet Hannah Maze. Ms. Maze teaches government, civics, and geography at A-J.

How are you handling your quarantine?

I’ve been deep cleaning my house, watching my nephew, hiking, running, and spending time with my nieces.

How are you trying to support your students while we’re on hiatus?

I have been posting materials on classroom daily and asking questions through remind 101 or classroom. I recently tried a video conference with my government students to provide a Q&A session for support through the app Zoom. It was very successful and I enjoyed getting to see my kids.

￼What are you currently learning that will likely benefit your students?

￼ I have been looking into how to do video lessons/conferences with students. I’m trying to adapt lessons from how I'd teach them in person to online platforms. I’m using Google Classroom a lot more, and learning about all of its features.

Continue to follow us to see how A-J teachers are one more reason to be #ajproud

post_text:
If you ever get the opportunity to relive high school, Mrs. Neitzer's classes should be high on your list of priorities.

Her Advanced Biology II students take an up close look at animal organization. Students viewed epithelial, connective, muscular, and nervous tissues. In addition, they examined the structure of tissues to better understand the relation of structure and function.

But if functional knowledge isn't on your list of priorities, I can bet interacting, engaging approaches to information would be.
In this example, Ecology students turned the gloom and doom of toxicology into a fun learning experience by creating games to start conversations with friends. After all, global environmental health begins at the local level.

Just a quick peek #insideourclassroom and one more reason to be #ajproud

Happy first Wildcat Wednesday of 2020!

Today we have the opportunity to celebrate the accomplishment of A-J student Madilyn Gawrych. On Saturday, Madi was named winner of District 15 (encompassing the 12 most southern counties of Illinois) for the VFW Voice of Democracy annual essay contest. While 14 students made it to the final round, more than 210 high school students from District 15 participated in the contest.

In recognition of her accomplishment, Madi received a plaque, a certificate, medals, other prizes, and $400. She now moves to the state competition to vie for monetary awards and scholarships.

Madi will be representing A-J at the state competition held February 7-9 in Springfield, IL.

We are so proud of you, Madi. You're one more reason to be #ajproud

post_text: Mrs. Penninger’s A.P. U.S. History class finished the semester learning about the Civil War and Reconstruction Era. Pictured are student historians displaying their work. They each formed an essential question about the era, researched and corroborated primary and secondary sources, and synthesized their interpretations on one page.

A-J students had the opportunity to meet potential future employers at today's career fair. This event was sponsored to give students the chance to discuss potential job or internship opportunities and establish professional relationships with a variety of employers and recruiters.

Because research indicates prepared students are successful students, events like our yearly career fair allow students to practice social competencies like communication, self-management, and social responsibility outside of the classroom.

One more reason to be #ajproud

post_text: Mrs. Falkenburry's advanced Algebra 2 class designed and built wooden catapults to launch skittles. Based on the fall due to gravity, the skittle's average time in air, and total distance traveled, they were able to develop equations for their skittle's parabolic path. They then had to mathematically adjust their initial equation to determine where the skittle would hit the ground if the launch took place from the top of a desk. Part of their final grade was based on the accuracy of their final launch. #intheclassroom #ajproud

After stunting with the team, #BenitoelBurro just decided to become part of the Wildcat Cheer Squad. And if he’s willing to try new things, might as well add new skills to the list, too. When a couple of boys offered to teach him photoshopping skills and the art of becoming a gamer, #TheAdventuresofBenitoelBurro got far more interesting. What else would we expect from the #AJStudentsofSpanishIV ? Thankfully, Benito’s benefactors remembered a burro’s gotta eat and took him for some wood fired pizza at Fat Bottom Betty’s.

Stay tuned for more adventures from #BenitoelBurro

post_text:
Join the A-J book club on December 5 for a discussion about the current book choice--Scythe by Neal Shusterman.

Two teens must learn the “art of killing” in this Printz Honor–winning book, the first in a chilling new series from Neal Shusterman, author of the New York Times bestselling Unwind dystology.

A world with no hunger, no disease, no war, no misery: humanity has conquered all those things, and has even conquered death. Now Scythes are the only ones who can end life—and they are commanded to do so, in order to keep the size of the population under control.

Citra and Rowan are chosen to apprentice to a scythe—a role that neither wants. These teens must master the “art” of taking life, knowing that the consequence of failure could mean losing their own.

Scythe is the first novel of a thrilling new series by National Book Award–winning author Neal Shusterman in which Citra and Rowan learn that a perfect world comes only with a heavy price.

post_text: Ms. Maze's government students have been learning about the Legislative Branch and how the House of Representatives is based off of population. Students learned about the Census taken every 10 years, and how those results lead to Redistricting or Gerrymandering. Today, students are learning first hand how redistricting occurs, and the 5 different ways a district could be Gerrymandered. #ajproud
